track_notes: Distance 11.9 miles.  This is a smooth dirt road that passenger vehicles can handle.  GPS track is included for this summit because there are no road signs and MANY turns.  At the end of this track is an active ranch.  While I didn’t meet the ranchers, it’s reported by previous hikers they are friendly towards hikers and hunters.  There is an informal campsite east of the ranch house, although I didn’t explore and find it.
track_title: Alma NM to Smoothing Camp Ranch

track_notes: Distance 2.9 miles.  From TH hike 0.5 miles on road.  Half tire at N33 19 41.6 W109 03 40.6.  Cairn (built  9/30/18 N33 19 41.5 W109 03 41.2) go downhill.  Follow road downhill to wash.  Enter wash N33 19 44.9 W109 03 46.4.  Many cattle bones in wash.  Exit wash N33 19 50.5 W109 03 41.6 on good trail going WNW.  Lots of cattle in the canyon.  Near the end of this trail I noticed numerous piles of fresh bear scat, but didn’t see any bears.  Notable waypoints: skull on tree N33 19 54.4 W109 04 00.0, old corral N33 19 55.6 W109 04 18.3, old corral N33 19 55.6 W109 04 22.6, waterfall N33 19 56.8 W109 04 35.3, gate N33 19 58.4 W109 05 44.3.

Distance 0.7 miles.  This is pretty straightforward portion of the trail to hike.  Horse Canyon Trail disappears after the cairn (at least I could not find it through many attempts).  Notable waypoints: rubble rocks N33 20 19.0 W109 05 52.7, stump N33 20 19.4 W109 05 51.8, cairn at end of this segment N33 20 18.5 W109 05 47.2.

Distance 0.4 miles.  Frustrated by not being able to find any semblance of a trail after the cairn, on the ascent I decided to take a shortcut directly up the hill to the ridge.  This uphill path was hacked by me through dense brush using a 8-inch blade folding saw.  If you take this route, bring a saw.  It’s steep, direct, and may be clogged with brush.  Notable waypoints: 300 foot segment of a trail that runs horizontal across mountain which didn’t seem to go anywhere useful N33 20 20.6 W109 05 46.4, ridgeline N33 20 30.9 W109 05 41.1.
track_title: Bushwhack from Cairn Uphill to Ridge

track_notes: Distance 1.1 miles.  Coming down I tried a different approach, hoping to find evidence of Horse Canyon Trail above the cairn.  I failed.  On the descent I crisscrossed the published trail location (on the lower east-west segment) and found no evidence of a trail.  No significant hacking of the brush was required to get through using this route, however, it is a longer route.  On the positive side, the portion of this segment on the ascent that runs from ESE to WNW is very pretty.  When I hiked it (Sept 2018) it was a clear meadow, I suspect from a fire in the last 25 years.  Notable waypoints, area cleared by fire N33 20 28.7 W109 05 25.0
track_title: Bushwhack from Cairn Across Mountain to Ridge

track_notes: Distance 0.6 miles.  While not always very obvious, the trail does exist and you should be able to push through without cutting any brush.  At the junction of fences (and a gate) you will head NE for about 30 feet.  Look for a chain of medium-sized tree limbs and rocks that will guide you to the NW.  I built a cairn (Sept 2018) that marks the beginning of a trail through THICK brush N33 20 36.9 W109° 05 54.6.  Trust this trail and push through!  The peak is covered with small trees, grasses, and nice views all around.  Plenty of room for a wire antenna.  Notable waypoints, gap in fence N33 20 48.5 W109 06 06.0
track_title: Horse Canyon Along Ridge to Peak

track_notes: Distance 2.5 miles.  This is a ROUGH dirt road with MANY large rocks.  Passenger vehicles will NOT survive this road!  My Subaru Forester managed to handle it, but I had to perform a lot of road maintenance:  removing large rocks, trimming trees, and maneuvering my vehicle through a serpentine of remaining rocks.  I did not attempt the last downhill stretch (about 500 ft) to the trailhead, as it was very steep and had a half dozen very large rocks.  Wildbunch TH would be a nice place to camp.  As an alternate, I camped (and others have) at N33 19 38.3 W109 03 10.9 and I did a few improvements to that site.
